inClass.set(\\\"demo.App\\\") }  tasks.named&lt;Test&gt;(\\\"test\\\") <span>{</span>     /\\ns3 17879 s3\\\")  ... } ...</code></pre>                     <p>Gradle automatically resolves the correct version of declared dependencies                         by using the information from the BOM.</p>                 </li></ol>         </li></ol></div><p>The following examples show complete Gradle build files in both the Kotlin and Groovy DSLs.         The build file contains dependencies for Amazon S3, authentication, logging, and testing. The         source and target version of Java is version 11.</\\n\"}], \"isError\": false, \"timestamp\": 1782328826073}]}\n[recv] {\"type\": \"turn_start\"}\n[recv] {\"type\": \"message_start\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"oca/gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 0, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"stop\", \"timestamp\": 1782328826081}}\n[assistant-event] thinking_start\n[assistant-event] thinking_end\n[assistant-event] text_start\n[assistant] {\n[assistant]   \"action\": \"advisory_preparation\",\n[assistant]   \"summary\": \"The requested artifact is the AWS SDK v2 BOM: a POM-only dependency-management artifact with no JAR/classes, so the normal scaffold cannot reach meaningful runtime or native-image coverage without adding an actual AWS SDK module managed by that BOM.\",\n[assistant]   \"deterministic_setup\": [\n[assistant]     {\n[assistant]       \"kind\": \"dependency\",\n[assistant]       \"coordinate\": \"software.amazon.awssdk:s3:2.44.11\",\n[assistant]       \"scope\": \"testImplementation\",\n[assistant]       \"reason\": \"AWS documents the BOM as dependency management for individual SDK clients; adding a real client module gives tests runtime classes and common AWS SDK reflection