p id.</p>       <p>If you created your Maven project in a different way, configure the latest version of the SDK for your project by ensuring that the <code class=\\\"code\\\">pom.xml</code> file contains the following.</p>       <pre class=\\\"programlisting\\\"><div \\ndependencyManagement 18709 dependencyManagement&gt;     &lt;dependencies&gt;       &lt;dependency&gt;         &lt;groupId&gt;software.amazon.awssdk&lt;/groupId&gt;         &lt;artifactId&gt;bom&lt;/artifactId&gt;         &lt;version&gt;$<span>{</span>aws.java.sdk.version}&lt;/version&gt;         &lt;type&gt;pom&lt;/type&gt;         &lt;scope&gt;import&lt;/scope&gt;       &lt;/dependency&gt;     &lt;/dependencies&gt;   &lt;/dependencyManagement&gt; &lt;/project&gt;</code></pre>       <div class=\\\"awsdocs-note\\\"><div class=\\\"a\\nplatform -1 \\ns3 13287 s3 -Dregion=US_WEST_2 \\\\  -DarchetypeVersion=<code class=\\\"replaceable\\\">2.X.X</code> \\\\  -DgroupId=com.example.myapp \\\\  -DartifactId=myapp</code></pre>     <div class=\\\"awsdocs-note\\\"><div class=\\\"awsdocs-note-title\\\"><awsui-icon name=\\\"status-info\\\" variant=\\\"link\\\"></awsui-icon><h6>Note</h6></div><div class=\\\"awsdocs-note-text\\\"><p>Replace <em>com.example.myapp</em> with the full package namespace of your         application. Also replace <em>myapp</em> with your project name. This becomes         the name\\n\\nURL https://docs.aws.amazon.com/sdk-for-java/latest/developer-guide/setup-project-gradle.html\\nbom 15984 BOM) for the AWS SDK for Java 2.x to the <code class=\\\"code\\\">dependencies</code>                         section of the  <code class=\\\"code\\\">build.gradle.kts</code> file.</p>                     <pre class=\\\"programlisting\\\"><div class=\\\"code-btn-container\\\"><div class=\\\"btn-copy-code\\\" title=\\\"Copy\\\"><awsui-icon name=\\\"copy\\\"></awsui-icon></div></div><!--DEBUG: cli (groovy)--><code class=\\\"groovy \\\">... dependencies <span>{</span>     implementation(platform(\\\"software.amazon.awssdk:bom:2.27.21\\\"))     // With\\ndependencyManagement -1 \\nplatform 15146 platform:junit-platform-launcher\\\")      // This dependency is used by the application.     implementation(\\\"com.google.guava:guava:33.3.0-jre\\\") }  // Apply a specific Java toolchain to ease working on different environments. java <span>{</span>     toolchain <span>{</span>         languageVersion.set(JavaLanguageVersion.of(11))     } }  application <span>{</span>     // Define the main class for the application.     mainClass.set(\\\"demo.App\\\") }  tasks.named&lt;Test&gt;(\\\"test\\\") <span>{</span>     /\\ns3 17879 s3\\\")  ... } ...</code></pre>                     <p>Gradle automatically resolves the correct version of declared dependencies                         by using the information from the BOM.</p>                 </li></ol>         </li></ol></div><p>The following examples show complete Gradle build files in both the Kotlin and Groovy DSLs.         The build file contains dependencies for Amazon S3, authentication, logging, and testing. The         source and target version of Java is version 11.</\\n\"}], \"isError\": false, \"timestamp\": 1782328826073}]}\n945:[assistant]   \"action\": \"advisory_preparation\",\n946:[assistant]   \"summary\": \"The requested artifact is the AWS SDK v2 BOM: a POM-only dependency-management artifact with no JAR/classes, so the normal scaffold cannot reach meaningful runtime or native-image coverage without adding an actual AWS SDK module managed by that BOM.\",\n947:[assistant]   \"deterministic_setup\": [\n950:[assistant]       \"coordinate\": \"software.amazon.awssdk:s3:2.44.11\",\n955:[assistant]   \"agent_guidance\": \"Do not rely on real AWS credentials, profiles, IMDS, or network access. Configure region and static dummy credentials explicitly in test code, use endpointOverride where a client is built, and inject a mock/stub SdkHttpClient for request/response coverage.\",\n956:[assistant]   \"risks\": [\n957:[assis